1 Abstract

This project is made with R markdown. To finish the project, we need to analyze the data of 18 sessions (Sessions 1 to 18) from four mice: Cori, Frossman, Hence, and Lederberg. The primary objective of this project is to build a predictive model to predict the outcome (feedback type) of each trial using the neural activity data (spike trains in spks), along with the stimuli (the left and right contrasts). To be more specific, the ultimate goal of the project is to predict the outcome (feedback_type) in the test set that contains 100 trials from Session 1 and Session 18. A total of 18 RDS files are provided that contain the records from 18 sessions. We can download these RDS files and the test data from the link provided on the Canvas course page.

2 Introduction

We need to analyze data from 18 sessions in this project. I find that there are 8 variables in each session. We can report mouse_name(the name of the mouse for specific sessions), date_exp(the date of the experiment), number of brain_area(the unique brain area involved), number of neurons, number of trials (the number of trials in each session), success rate for each session(the ratio of successful trials to the total number of trials) (6 in total). Data structure differs across sessions. For instance, Session 1 contains 734 neurons from 8 brain areas, where Session 2 contains 1070 neurons from 5 brain areas. Each session comprised several hundred trials. Following variables are available for each trial:

  • feedback_type: type of the feedback, 1 for success and -1 for failure
  • contrast_left: contrast of the left stimulus
  • contrast_right: contrast of the right stimulus
  • time: centers of the time bins for spks
  • spks: numbers of spikes of neurons in the visual cortex in time bins defined in time
  • brain_area: area of the brain where each neuron lives

Take the 11th trial in Session 5 for example, we can see that the left contrast for this trial is 1 the right contrast is 0, and the feedback (outcome) of the trial is 1. There are a total of 1077 meurons in this trial from 10 areas of the brain. The primary objective of this project is to build a predictive model to predict the outcome (feedback type) of each trial using the neural activity data (spike trains in spks), along with the stimuli (the left and right contrasts). To define neural activities, we can take the average number of spikes across neurons in each brain area as the activities. To develop my projects in the next sections, I’m thinking about some questions of interest:

  • Is there a relationship between the contrast levels of the stimuli (left and right) and the feedback type (success or failure) in the trials? Can this relationship be used to predict the feedback type?

  • How does the success rate vary across different mice and sessions?

    This question explores the overall performance of the mice and sessions. By examining the success rates in different sessions and for different mice, I can identify any variations or trends that might influence the outcome prediction and provide insights into the reliability of the data.

  • Are there any interactions or relationships between the neural activity and the success rate across sessions?

  • Can we predict the outcome (feedback type) of each trial based on the neural activity (e.g., average number of spikes, firing rate) and stimulus contrasts?

    This is the primary objective of my project. By building a predictive model using the neural activity data (spike trains) and stimulus contrasts as features, I aim to predict the feedback type (success or failure) of each trial. This question focuses on developing a reliable model for outcome prediction.

  • Do different brain areas exhibit distinct patterns of neural activity during the decision-making process?

    This question explores the variability in neural activity across different brain areas. By comparing the activity patterns of neurons from different brain areas, I can investigate if certain areas play specific roles in decision-making.

  • Are there specific brain areas or neurons that are more strongly associated with successful outcomes? Can the activity of these neurons be used to predict the feedback type?

Predicting trial outcomes based on neural activity and stimuli can contribute to our knowledge of how the brain processes visual information and makes decisions. The key variables for building the prediction model include stimulus contrasts, feedback types, and neural activity. My assumption is that higher average spike counts may lead to more neural activities in brain areas when the stimuli is presented to mice. The brain area with the most neural activities will become the most helpful area for mice to give a correct feedback. I will try to address the questions of interest I mentioned above in the section of descriptive analysis and the section of data integration. I will use table, ggplot, bar plot, scatter plot, the Benchmark method, and the other visualizations to show my findings more clearly. In the section of prediction modeling, I’d like to build a linear regression model and a logistic regression model to predict the feedback types of mice using the data values of contrast level and average spike activity as predictors, and I will try to use data values from two test sets to test the performance of my logistic regression model.

3 Background

In the study conducted by Steinmetz et al. (2019), experiments were performed on a total of 10 mice over 39 sessions. Each session comprised several hundred trials, during which visual stimuli were randomly presented to the mouse on two screens positioned on both sides of it. The stimuli varied in terms of contrast levels, which took values in {0, 0.25, 0.5, 1}, with 0 indicating the absence of a stimulus. The mice were required to make decisions based on the visual stimuli, using a wheel controlled by their forepaws. A reward or penalty (i.e., feedback) was subsequently administered based on the outcome of their decisions. In particular,

  • When left contrast > right contrast, success (1) if turning the wheel to the right and failure (-1) otherwise.
  • When right contrast > left contrast, success (1) if turning the wheel to the left and failure (-1) otherwise.
  • When both left and right contrasts are zero, success (1) if holding the wheel still and failure (-1) otherwise.
  • When left and right contrasts are equal but non-zero, left or right will be randomly chosen (50%) as the correct choice.

The activity of the neurons in the mice’s visual cortex was recorded during the trials and made available in the form of spike trains, which are collections of timestamps corresponding to neuron firing. In this project, we focus specifically on the spike trains of neurons from the onset of the stimuli to 0.4 seconds post-onset. In addition, we only use 18 sessions (Sessions 1 to 18) from four mice: Cori, Frossman, Hence, and Lederberg.

5 Data Integration

  1. Calculating average spike counts during a trial.
## [1] 1.581744
  • I learned this Benchmark method from course project consulting. Our goal in the project is to predict the outcome ( like feedback type) in the test set that contains 100 trials from Session 1 and Session 18. Based on our exploration in previous sections, we know that data structure differs across sessions since number of neurons, number of brain areas, and number of trials are different across 18 sessions. The heterogeneity is due to the differences in neurons measured in each session, so we can ignore the information about specific neurons by averaging over their activities by using this benchmark method. For each trial in a session, we can first take the summation of spikes for each neuron, which results in a vector that contains the total number of spikes for all neurons during the 0.4 seconds in that trial, and then we take the average of the total number of spikes, which results in one number that is the average spike counts during that trial.

  • When I know how to calculate average spike counts during a trial, I create a table to display more detail information in a session, taking session 5 as an example. From the table, we can see that there are 10 brain areas and 254 trials in session 5. The values in the columns of brain areas indicates the average number of spikes recorded across all neurons in a specific brain area during a given trial. It provides an indication of the overall level of neuronal activity in that area during the trial. The “avg_spikes” column provides the overall average spike count for each trial, regardless of the brain area. If we take a specific trial, the “avg_spikes” value will give us the average spike count across all brain areas combined. Left Contrast is the contrast level associated with the left stimulus during the trial. This value represents the strength or intensity of the stimulus presented on the left side. Similarly, Right Contrast is the contrast level associated with the right stimulus during the trial. This value represents the strength or intensity of the stimulus presented on the right side. The feedback type associated with the trial, and it indicates the outcome or response received from the mouse during the trial. This is binary, indicating correct(1) or incorrect(-1) feedback.Trial id is an unique identifier for each trial, and it allows us to track and identify individual trials. We can use this table to compare the average spike activity across different brain areas within each trial and summarize how the overall average spike count for each trial is related to the feedback outcome. In a general trend, the overall average spike count for each trial tend to be higher when the mouse gives a correct feedback(labeled with value 1). Therefore, combining all the information of spikes activity across 10 brain areas in each trial, we can say that even though each brain area has different levels of neuronal activity, a higher level of activity across the whole brain made the mouse more likely to make the right decision.

However, based on the table in section 4.1, the success rate for mouse Hench (session 8) to give a correct feedback is 0.64, and the success rate for mouse Lederberg (session 13) is 0.8. The neural activities from the other brain areas may interfere the mind of mice and even reduce the success rate of feedback. It helps to enhance my hypothesis that mouse with brain that perform higher level of neural activities in general are more likely to be successful in a trial, and the brain area with the highest average spike count contributes most to the mouse’s correct choice.

I first use a linear regression model to predict the feedback of mice using the data values of contrast level and average spike activity as predictors. I combined the information about each session which include attributes like spks(spike data), contrast level values, feedback values and id variable. I defined the average spike area function to calculates the average spike activity for a given set of spike data. In the model, the nested loops iterate over each session and trial, extracting the spike data from each session and calculating the average spike activity using the average_spike_area function. The calculated values, along with the corresponding contrast level values, feedback values, and id, are stored in the trial.summary data frame. In the summary of this prediction model, we will find the summary statistics and coefficients of the fitted regression model. From the model summary, we get an F-statistic of infinity which suggests an extremely high ratio of explained to unexplained variance. The p-value associated with the F-statistic is reported as “< 2.2e-16”. This extremely low p-value suggests that the model is statistically significant and that at least one of the predictor variables has a significant impact on the outcome variable. In general, for this prediction model, a very high F-statistic and an extremely low p-value suggest that the model is highly significant and provides valuable information for predicting the outcome variable (feedback) based on the chosen predictors (contrast levels and average spike activity). To compare which method is better for building the prediction model, I will also apply logistic regression method to build the model and use test data from session 1 and session 18 to see its performance.

In the model using logistic regression method, we still predict the feedback of mice using the data values of contrast level and average spike activity as predictors. We first read two test sets using the readRDS function and stores them in a list called ‘test’. To extract relevant data, I create a new list called test_data and populates it with a subset of the test data. For each test set, I select the first 100 elements of the spks, contrast, feedback, and id variables and stores them in a separate sublist within test_data.To calculate average spike activities, I initialize a data frame called test_summary with 100 rows and columns for average_spike_area, contrast, feedback, and id, then I calculate the average spike area for each trial in the test sets and fills in the corresponding values in test_summary. From the summary of the model, we can see the information about the coefficients, standard errors, z-values, and p-values for the predictors. The number of Fisher scoring iterations tells us that 7 iterations are required for the optimization algorithm to converge and estimate the parameters of the logistic regression model. The AIC value is a measure of the relative quality of a statistical model, balancing goodness of fit and model complexity. In this model, AIC value of 11.396 suggests that the model provides a good balance between fit and complexity. It indicates that the model has a relatively low level of information loss and is likely to be a reasonable representation of the relationship between the predictors (contrast and average spike activity) and the feedback. The lower the AIC value, the better the model performance.

8 Discussion

In this project, after doing the data exploration and data integration, we have several assumptions about the relationship between the neural activities of mice brains and the feedback given by the mice. For mice, each brain area has different levels of neuronal activity, a higher level of activity across the whole brain made a mouse more likely to make the correct decision. Mouse with brain that perform higher level of neural activities in general are more likely to be successful in a trial, and the brain area with the highest average spike count contributes most to the mouse’s correct choice. However, only one helpful brain area is not enough to help mice to make a good choice since the neural activities from the other brain areas may interfere the mind of mice and even reduce the success rate of feedback. If a mouse use two areas (having the highest average spike count among all brain areas across 18 sessions) from session 8 and session 13 at the same time to make a decision, I believe that its success rate to give a correct feedback will be higher. In the end of the project, I build a linear regression model and a logistic regression model to predict the feedback types of mice using the data values of contrast level and average spike activity as predictors, and I use data values from two test sets to test the performance of my logistic regression model.The results from both models suggest that contrast and average spike activity are reliable predictors to predict the outcome(feedback type). It indicates that average spike counts could has a significant impact on the feedback type from mice, and my previous assumptions could be true.

# Define a function to calculate average spike counts for each area during a trial
average_spike_area <- function(i.t, this_session) {
  spk.trial <- this_session$spks[[i.t]]
  area <- this_session$brain_area
  spk.count <- apply(spk.trial, 1, sum)
  spk.average.tapply <- tapply(spk.count, area, mean)
  return(spk.average.tapply)
}

plot.trial <- function(i.t, area, area.col, this_session) {
  spks <- this_session$spks[[i.t]]
  n.neuron <- dim(spks)[1]
  time.points <- this_session$time[[i.t]]
  
  plot(0, 0, xlim = c(min(time.points), max(time.points)), ylim = c(0, n.neuron + 1), col = 'white',
       xlab = 'Time (s)', yaxt = 'n', ylab = 'Neuron',
       main = paste('Trial', i.t, 'Feedback:', this_session$feedback_type[i.t]), cex.lab = 1.5)
  
  for (i in 1:n.neuron) {
    i.a <- which(area == this_session$brain_area[i])
    col.this <- area.col[i.a]
    
    ids.spike <- which(spks[i, ] > 0)  # find out when there are spikes
    if (length(ids.spike) > 0) {
      points(x = time.points[ids.spike], y = rep(i, length(ids.spike)), pch = '.', cex = 2, col = col.this)
    }
  }
  
  legend("topright",
         legend = area,
         col = area.col,
         pch = 16,
         cex = 0.8)
}

In this project, the data of 18 sessions (Sessions 1 to 18) from four mice (Cori, Frossman, Hence, and Lederberg) and the test data I used to test the model performance are all downloaded from the link provided in Canvas course page of STA 141A. I learned the background of mice experiment from html file of course project description in Canvas and the website https://doi.org/10.1038/s41586-019-1787-x. The code I used in this project is modified based on the code I learned from the html file of project consulting on 5/5/2023 (under week 5 on Canvas) and the html file of project consulting on 5/26/2023 (under week 8 on Canvas). Some code and analysis toward the model I used for the project is also modified based on the suggestions I learned from ChatGPT https://chat.openai.com/. Lectures materials and Jupyter notes in Canvas provide me thoughts to write the code too.

  • html file of project consulting on 5/5/2023 (under week 5 on Canvas)
  • html file of project consulting on 5/26/2023 (under week 8 on Canvas)

  • Data sets download from sessions.zip link ( under file of course project description in Canvas)
  • Test data download from test.zip link in Canvas
